{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:29:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:29:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.59,0.3,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89836"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74027"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2245"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39232"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89836"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is brought to a rural hospital after sustaining a stab wound to her left chest during a physical altercation. The nearest tertiary hospital is 200 km away. The emergency consultant is currently managing a critical patient and will not be available for 20 minutes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she is anxious, with a blood pressure of 106/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min, respiratory rate 28/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 94% on room air. On inspection of her chest a wound measuring approximately 5 cm in diameter is visible below her left scapula, with air movement noted through the wound as she breathes. On auscultation there are decreased breath sounds on the left side of her chest.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wait for consultant to perform intercostal chest drain","Arrange immediate helicopter transfer","Three-way occlusive wound dressing","Needle decompression","Intubation with laryngeal mask airway"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of an open pneumothorax including anxiety, tachypnoea and decreased breath sounds on the affected side of the chest. Furthermore, air movement is noted through the wound during inspiration, confirming the presence of an open communication between the pleural space and the external environment. Open pneumothorax, or sucking chest wound, results in air being drawn into the pleural space during inspiration, leading to ineffective ventilation and potential hypoxia and respiratory compromise. Given this occurs in a rural setting with limited immediate specialist support, the priority is to stabilise the patient while awaiting definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree-way occlusive wound dressing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step. The dressing acts as a flutter valve, allowing air to escape from the pleural space during expiration, thus preventing the development of tension pneumothorax as well as preventing further air entry into the pleural space during inspiration. This temporising measure can be performed safely by any trained healthcare provider and helps stabilise the patient\u0027s condition while awaiting specialist input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaiting for the consultant\u003C/strong\u003E to perform an intercostal chest drain without first addressing the open pneumothorax would leave the patient at risk of deterioration. While chest drain insertion will be necessary, the immediate priority is to seal the chest wall defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging immediate helicopter transfer\u003C/strong\u003E without first stabilising the patient could be dangerous. The patient requires initial stabilisation before transport can be safely undertaken. Transfer arrangements should be made after initial stabilisation measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the primary intervention for an open pneumothorax. It is reserved for closed or tension pneumothorax, where urgent decompression of the chest cavity is required and has to be achieved before a formal chest drain can be inserted. A tension (or decompensated) pneumothorax is a clinical diagnosis based on clinical instability secondary to a pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation with laryngeal mask airway\u003C/strong\u003E without first addressing the chest wall defect could worsen the situation by creating positive pressure in the chest cavity. This intervention should be reserved for patients with respiratory failure despite other measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter applying the occlusive dressing, the next steps would include administering oxygen, establishing IV access, providing analgesia, activating retrieval services, and closely monitoring the patient while awaiting the consultant\u0027s availability for chest drain insertion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a rural setting without immediate specialist support, a three-way occlusive dressing is an essential temporising measure for open pneumothorax.","Supplemental oxygen and close monitoring are crucial steps in the management of a pneumothorax while awaiting definitive management.","Early communication with retrieval services should be initiated for patients with chest trauma in rural settings."],"references":["Kong VY, Liu M, Sartorius B, Clarke DL. Open pneumothorax: the spectrum and outcome of management based on Advanced Trauma Life Support recommendations. Eur J Trauma Emerg Surg. 2015 Aug;41(4):401-4. Available at: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/268872645_Open_pneumothorax_the_spectrum_and_outcome_of_management_based_on_Advanced_Trauma_Life_Support_recommendations"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74027"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74027"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T08:26:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T08:28:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6142"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89836"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","